  <front>
   <head>[MORAL SONG] III. The ROSE.</head>
  </front>
  <body>
   <lg xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" type="poem">
    <lg n="1" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="1" met="--+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="12">HOW fair is the Rose? what a beau Flow'r?</l>
     <l n="2" met="--+|--+|--+" line_length="9">The Glory of April and May:</l>
     <l n="3" met="--+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="12">But the Leaves are beginning to fade in an Hour,</l>
     <l n="4" met="--+|--+|--+" line_length="9">And they wither and die in a Day.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="2" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="5" met="--+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="12">Yet the Rose has one powerful Virtue to boast,</l>
     <l n="6" met="--+|--+|--+" line_length="9">Above all the Flowers of the Field:</l>
     <l n="7" met="--+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="12">When its Leaves are all dead, and fine Colours are lost,</l>
     <l n="8" met="--+|--+|--+" line_length="9">Still how sweet a Perfume it will yield?</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="3" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="9" met="--+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="12">So frail is the Youth and the Beauty of Men,</l>
     <l n="10" met="--+|--+|--+" line_length="9">Tho' they bloom and look gay like the Rose:</l>
     <l n="11" met="--+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="12">But all our fond Care to preserve them is vain;</l>
     <l n="12" met="--+|--+|--+" line_length="9">Time kills them as fast as he goes.</l>
    </lg>
    <lg n="4" stanza_type="quatrain">
     <l n="13" met="--+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="12">Then I'll not be proud of my Youth or my Beauty,</l>
     <l n="14" met="--+|--+|--+" line_length="9">Since both of them wither and fade:</l>
     <l n="15" met="--+|--+|--+|--+" line_length="12">But gain a good Name by well-doing my Duty;</l>
     <l n="16" met="--+|--+|--+" line_length="9">This will scent like a Rose when I'm dead.</l>
    </lg>
   </lg>
